=3D"body-n0vxv prose-mhScE prose-MpLPk article__body-JuzOb"><p class=3D"" d=
ata-block=3D"sciam/paragraph">Is 170,141,183,460,469,231,731,687,303,715,88=
4,105,727 prime? Before you ask the Internet for an answer, can you conside=
r how you might answer that question <i>without</i> a computer or even a di=
gital calculator?</p><p class=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/paragraph">In the 18=
00s French mathematician =C3=89douard Lucas spent years proving that this 3=
9-digit number was indeed prime. How did he do it? Lucas, who incidentally =
also designed the entertaining game <a href=3D"https://www.scientificameric=
an.com/game/math-puzzle-move-tower/">Tower of Hanoi</a>, developed a method=
 that=E2=80=99s still useful today, more than a century later.</p><div clas=
s=3D"breakoutContainer-UppO6"><gpt-ad class=3D"ad-Xtmn1" unitpath=3D"inject=
or" id-format=3D"gpt-unit-{}" sizes-from-0=3D"320x450,300x250,300x50,320x50=
,fluid" sizes-from-745=3D"320x450,728x90,300x250,fluid" sizes-from-1000=3D"=
970x350,970x250,970x90,728x90,300x250,fluid" targeting-pos=3D"article-1" st=
yle=3D"--margin: 0.25rem 0 1.25rem;"></gpt-ad></div><p class=3D"" data-bloc=
k=3D"sciam/paragraph">People have been fascinated by prime numbers for mill=
ennia. These numbers are divisible only by 1 and themselves, whereas every =
other integer can be uniquely expressed as the product of several prime num=
bers; for example, 15 =3D 3 =C3=97 5. Prime numbers essentially form the pe=
riodic table of mathematics. They also hold many secrets. They appear on th=
e number line with a certain regularity, but their occurrence is characteri=
zed by fluctuations that cannot yet be quantified. This unpredictability ha=
s been a source of consternation for experts.</p><p class=3D"" data-block=
=3D"sciam/paragraph">And math enthusiasts are constantly seeking new prime =
numbers. <a href=3D"https://www.spektrum.de/news/primzahlen-gimps-praesenti=
ert-die-bisher-groesste-primzahl-m52/2238897">The current record</a> (as of=
 October 2025) for the largest prime is 2<sup>136,279,841</sup> =E2=88=92 1=
, a number with 41,024,320 digits. Simply reading this number aloud would t=
ake approximately 240 days.</p><h2 id=3D"prime-numbers-with-a-special-struc=
ture" class=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/heading"><b>Prime Numbers with a Speci=
al Structure</b></h2><p class=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/paragraph">Anyone wh=
o has observed the record-breaking prime numbers of recent years may have n=
oticed that they mostly have a similar structure: 2<i><sup>p</sup></i> =E2=
=80=93 1 (where <i>p</i> is a prime number). Prime numbers of this form are=
 called Mersenne primes. And the number to which Lucas dedicated almost two=
 decades of his life is also a Mersenne prime, namely 2<sup>127</sup> =E2=
=80=93 1. But there=E2=80=99s some trickiness to these Mersenne primes: not=
 every 2<i><sup>p</sup></i>=E2=80=93 1 is a prime number for every prime va=
lue of <i>p. </i>For example, 2<sup>11</sup> =E2=80=93 1 yields 2,047 and c=
an be written as the product of 23 and 89.</p><div class=3D"breakoutContain=
er-UppO6"><gpt-ad class=3D"ad-Xtmn1" unitpath=3D"injector" id-format=3D"gpt=
-unit-{}" sizes-from-0=3D"320x450,300x250,300x50,320x50,fluid" sizes-from-7=
45=3D"320x450,728x90,300x250,fluid" sizes-from-1000=3D"970x350,970x250,970x=
90,728x90,300x250,fluid" targeting-pos=3D"article-2" style=3D"--margin: 0.2=
5rem 0 1.25rem;"></gpt-ad></div><p class=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/paragraph=
">So in the mid-19th century Lucas wondered whether 2<sup>127</sup> =E2=80=
=93 1 was prime or not. He faced a formidable challenge. The number is enor=
mous, consisting of 39 digits, and at that time Lucas obviously didn=E2=80=
=99t have access to a computer. He had to manually ensure that 2<sup>127</s=
up> =E2=80=93 1 had no divisors (except 1 and itself).</p><p class=3D"" dat=
a-block=3D"sciam/paragraph">One way to accomplish this feat is to go throug=
h all prime numbers up to 2<sup>127</sup> =E2=80=93 1 and make sure it does=
 not divide by any of them. But this is extremely time-consuming and simply=
 infeasible if you don=E2=80=99t know all the smaller prime numbers.</p><h2=
 id=3D"the-lucas-lehmer-prime-number-test" class=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/h=
eading"><b>The Lucas-Lehmer Prime Number Test</b></h2><p class=3D"" data-bl=
ock=3D"sciam/paragraph">Lucas didn=E2=80=99t give up. He developed a novel =
method based on the findings of his colleague =C3=89variste Galois that req=
uired significantly less computation.</p><aside class=3D"readThisNext-cHtRr=
