://www.scientificamerican.com/author/max-springer/">Max Springer</a></p></d=
iv></li></ul><div class=3D"readThisNext_view_report_wrap-oEdOe"></div></asi=
de><p class=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/paragraph">Before we delve into the be=
autiful=E2=80=94but admittedly abstract=E2=80=94mathematics of Galois and L=
ucas, I=E2=80=99ll present Lucas=E2=80=99s result, now known as the Lucas-L=
ehmer primality test.</p><p class=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/paragraph">To ch=
eck whether 2<i><sup>p</sup></i> =E2=80=93 1 is prime, Lucas developed the =
following algorithm:</p><ol class=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/list"><li><p>Cre=
ate a sequence of numbers whose first term is <i>s</i><sub>0 </sub>=3D 4 an=
d where each subsequent <i>s</i><i><sub>n</sub></i> is calculated as <i>s</=
i><sup>2</sup><i><sub>n </sub></i><sub>=E2=80=93 1</sub> =E2=80=93 2. The s=
equence is therefore: 4, 14, 194, 37,634, and so on.</p></li><li><p>Then 2<=
i><sup>p</sup></i> =E2=80=93 1 is a prime number if and only if the <i>p</i=
> =E2=80=93 2nd term of the sequence (that is, <i>s</i><i><sub>p </sub></i>=
<sub>=E2=80=93 2</sub>) is divisible by 2<i><sup>p</sup></i> =E2=80=93 1 wi=
thout a remainder. That is to say, every Mersenne prime has this property, =
and conversely, every <i>s</i><i><sub>p </sub></i><sub>=E2=80=93 2</sub> de=
fines a Mersenne prime 2<i><sup>p</sup></i> =E2=80=93 1.</p></li></ol><p cl=
ass=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/paragraph">So instead of dividing the Mersenne=
 number by all prime numbers less than 2<sup>127</sup> =E2=80=93 1, it suff=
ices to perform calculations to determine <i>s</i><sub>125</sub> and then d=
ivide by 2<sup>127</sup> =E2=80=93 1. That=E2=80=99s much simpler, right?</=
p><div class=3D"breakoutContainer-UppO6"><gpt-ad class=3D"ad-Xtmn1" unitpat=
h=3D"injector" id-format=3D"gpt-unit-{}" sizes-from-0=3D"320x450,300x250,30=
0x50,320x50,fluid" sizes-from-745=3D"320x450,728x90,300x250,fluid" sizes-fr=
om-1000=3D"970x350,970x250,970x90,728x90,300x250,fluid" targeting-pos=3D"ar=
ticle-3" style=3D"--margin: 0.25rem 0 1.25rem;"></gpt-ad></div><p class=3D"=
" data-block=3D"sciam/paragraph">In practice, there=E2=80=99s just one tiny=
=E2=80=94or rather, very big=E2=80=94problem. The sequence terms <i>s</i><i=
><sub>n</sub></i> grow extremely fast=E2=80=94so fast, in fact, that it=E2=
=80=99s not particularly practical to work with them. Therefore, experts re=
sort to a trick: they divide the sequence terms <i>s</i><i><sub>n</sub></i>=
 by the Mersenne number and continue with the remainder if the division doe=
sn=E2=80=99t result in a whole number. This doesn=E2=80=99t change the seco=
nd part of the algorithm, so the condition for Mersenne primes remains the =
same: they must be able to evenly divide <i>s</i><i><sub>p</sub></i><sub> =
=E2=80=93 2</sub>. This trick does make <i>s</i><i><sub>p</sub></i><sub> =
=E2=80=93 2 </sub>significantly smaller, however.</p><p class=3D"" data-blo=
ck=3D"sciam/paragraph">To better understand the primality test, we can work=
 through it using a simple example: the Mersenne number 2=E2=81=B5 =E2=80=
=93 1, which is 31. Using the algorithm developed by Lucas, we need to calc=
ulate <i>s</i><sub>3</sub>, which is 37,634. Dividing this number by 31 giv=
es us the exact result 1,214. This means that <i>s</i><sub>3 </sub><i>is</i=
> divisible by 2<sup>5</sup> =E2=80=93 1, and therefore, the latter is a pr=
ime number.</p><p class=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/paragraph">After years of =
painstaking work, Lucas developed this primality test and applied it to 2<s=
up>127</sup> =E2=80=93 1. He was thus able to show that it was indeed a pri=
me number. To this day, it remains the largest prime number found without t=
he aid of a computer.</p><div class=3D"breakoutContainer-UppO6"><gpt-ad cla=
ss=3D"ad-Xtmn1" unitpath=3D"injector" id-format=3D"gpt-unit-{}" sizes-from-=
0=3D"320x450,300x250,300x50,320x50,fluid" sizes-from-745=3D"320x450,728x90,=
300x250,fluid" sizes-from-1000=3D"970x350,970x250,970x90,728x90,300x250,flu=
id" targeting-pos=3D"article-4" style=3D"--margin: 0.25rem 0 1.25rem;"></gp=
t-ad></div><p class=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/paragraph">Lucas did not concl=
usively prove that his method reliably identified Mersenne primes, however.=
 This was only achieved by mathematician Derrick Henry Lehmer in 1930, whic=
h is why the method is known as the Lucas-Lehmer primality test.</p><h2 id=
=3D"finite-number-sets" class=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/heading"><b>Finite N=
umber Sets</b></h2><p class=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/paragraph">But why doe=
s this strategy work at all? In fact, the proof is quite technical=E2=80=94=
and therefore, I=E2=80=99ll spare you the details (available <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucas%E2%80%93Lehmer_primality_test">on Wikipedi=
a</a>). But I can roughly outline the idea behind the method.</p><p class=
=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/paragraph">The Lucas-Lehmer primality test is bas=
ed on the research of Galois, who investigated symmetries in various mathem=
atical objects at the beginning of the 19th century. Unlike his predecessor=
s, however, he did not limit himself to geometric figures but also consider=
ed the symmetries of equations or number fields. The latter term describes =
a set of numbers in which all four basic arithmetic operations (that is, ad=
dition, subtraction, multiplication and division) can be applied without le=
aving the set. In other words, if I add or divide two numbers from the set,=
 I get a number that is also part of the set. Examples of number sets are t=
he rational numbers (which include integers and fractions) or the real numb=
ers.</p><div class=3D"breakoutContainer-UppO6"><gpt-ad class=3D"ad-Xtmn1" u=
nitpath=3D"injector" id-format=3D"gpt-unit-{}" sizes-from-0=3D"320x450,300x=
250,300x50,320x50,fluid" sizes-from-745=3D"320x450,728x90,300x250,fluid" si=
zes-from-1000=3D"970x350,970x250,970x90,728x90,300x250,fluid" targeting-pos=
=3D"article-5" style=3D"--margin: 0.25rem 0 1.25rem;"></gpt-ad></div><p cla=
ss=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/paragraph">But it turns out that there are smal=
ler number sets containing only a finite number of integers from 0 to <i>p<=
/i> =E2=80=93 1. To preserve the properties of a set, the numbers must be c=
ontinued periodically; after <i>p</i> =E2=80=93 1, 0 follows again: (0, 1, =
2, 3, ..., <i>p</i> =E2=80=93 1, 0, 1, 2, ...). Such so-called finite field=
s may seem strange, but in fact, we encounter them in daily life: on an ana=
log clock, it is perfectly natural that 1 follows 12.</p><p class=3D"" data=
-block=3D"sciam/paragraph">As it turns out, finite number systems are a fie=
ld if and only if <i>p</i> is a prime number. And Galois discovered that th=
ese finite number fields possess special symmetric properties. Lucas exploi=
ted this principle in developing his primality test: If 2<sup>127</sup> =E2=
=80=93 1 is a prime number, then the corresponding number field 0, 1, 2,...=
, 2<sup>127</sup> =E2=80=93 2 must possess certain symmetrical properties. =
To generate this finite number system, you must divide all values greater t=
han 2<sup>127</sup> =E2=80=93 1 by 2<sup>127</sup> =E2=80=93 1 and calculat=
e the remainder. This is the final step in Lucas=E2=80=99s algorithm.</p><p=
 class=3D"" data-block=3D"sciam/paragraph"><i>This article originally appea=
red in </i>Spektrum der Wissenschaft <i>and was reproduced with permission.=
